ed accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aMade up of both material and symbolic elements, the urban space is always dynamic and transitional; it brings together or separates the past and the present, the public and the private, the center and the periphery. The present volume focuses on the interaction between the social processes and spatial forms that shape the identity of Italian cities. Using both canonical and less well-known texts along with cultural artifacts, the essays in the volume deprovincialize the Italian city, interpreting the material and symbolic practices that have made it into a unique entity whose enduring influence extends far outside Italy.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 0aCities and townszItalyxHistory. 0aPublic spaceszItalyxHistory. 4aArt and Material Culture. 4aEarly Modern Studies. 4aHigh Middle Ages. 4aHistory, Art History, and Archaeology. 4aMedieval Studies. 4aModern History. 7aARCHITECTURE / History / Renaissance.2bisacsh  aUrban Cultures, Italian Cultures, Representations of Urban Spaces.1 aAverett, Matthew Knox, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCannamela, Danila, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCastaldo, Achille, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCecchini, Isabella, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGarvin, Diana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGemmani, Lucia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGillen, Samantha, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHafer, Abbey, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPatat, Ellen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.lo